{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488488","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488488"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:43:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:43:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"458"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"458","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/458"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.13,0.5,0.16,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"458"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114830"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"458","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/458"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"458"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96834"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"2411"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5334"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6214"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44465"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114830","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114830"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old man presents to his General Practitioner with a painless abdominal swelling which has been present for 12 months and is slowly getting larger. He has no significant medical history including no surgical procedures, and he takes no regular medications. On examination he appears well. His BMI is 35 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. The swelling is evident when he lifts both legs off the bed (Images 1 - 2)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Abdominal ultrasound","CT abdomen","Provide advice on weight reduction and exercise","Advise hernia repair after weight reduction","Proceed to hernia repair"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a case of divarication of the recti which has a classic sign of bulging of abdominal muscles when abdominal muscles are contracted. The rectus abdominus muscles have become weakened and lax. With an increased abdominal girth (excessive weight) the linea alba stretches - but the fascia of the rectus muscles remains intact. This is often mistaken for an incisional hernia, with unnecessary investigations and referral for \u0027repair.\u0027\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPhysical exam of the abdomen could be done to look for any reducible hernia. If a hernia is suspected, \u003Cstrong\u003Eabdominal ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E could be considered as a bedside test.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHernia repair\u003C/strong\u003E is considered if the patient was symptomatic and affecting quality of life. Strangulated/Incarcerated hernia would require urgent surgical intervention, often a laparotomy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf patient was symptomatic, divarication of the recti is still a differential but other causes of abdominal pain should be explored which is often done through \u003Cstrong\u003ECT abdomen.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETherefore, asymptomatic with no clinical suspicion for other abdominal pathologies then first line of treatment should be lifestyle modification i.e. \u003Cstrong\u003Eweight reduction and exercise.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Divarication of recti is commonly acquired in pregnancy and obese patients."],"references":["Jessen ML, \u00d6berg S, Rosenberg J. Treatment Options for Abdominal Rectus Diastasis. Front Surg. 2019;6:65. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31803753/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96834"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"458"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15566"},{"type":"media","id":"15567"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15566","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15566"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ff818c6a-a2bc-40c8-a89e-649d814a1c5c.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ff818c6a-a2bc-40c8-a89e-649d814a1c5c.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"media","id":"15567","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15567"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/a72f8848-495e-43ea-9d1b-22e2fdf2276c.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/a72f8848-495e-43ea-9d1b-22e2fdf2276c.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96834","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96834"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-20T17:41:46+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-20T17:41:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"458"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114830"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","na